1. Azure DevOps Services
Azure DevOps consists of several core services:
a. Azure Repos (Source Control)
â€¢	Supports Git (distributed) and TFVC (centralized).
â€¢	Helps teams collaborate on code using branching, merging, and pull requests.
b. Azure Pipelines (CI/CD)
â€¢	Automates build and release processes.
â€¢	Supports Continuous Integration (CI) to test code automatically.
â€¢	Supports Continuous Deployment (CD) to deploy applications across environments.
â€¢	Works with multiple platforms (Windows, Linux, macOS) and supports YAML-based pipeline definitions.
c. Azure Boards (Project Management)
â€¢	Provides Kanban boards, Scrum boards, and backlog management.
â€¢	Helps teams track work items, issues, and sprints.
d. Azure Test Plans (Testing)
â€¢	Supports manual and automated testing.
â€¢	Helps in tracking test cases, test execution, and reporting.
e. Azure Artifacts (Package Management)
â€¢	Provides a repository for storing NuGet, npm, Maven, and Python packages.
â€¢	Helps manage dependencies securely.
________________________________________
2. CI/CD Workflow in Azure DevOps
A typical CI/CD pipeline in Azure DevOps follows these steps:
1.	Developers push code to Azure Repos.
2.	CI Pipeline triggers automated builds and tests.
3.	Artifacts (built files) are stored in Azure Artifacts.
4.	CD Pipeline deploys the application to various environments.
5.	Monitoring and feedback loop ensures continuous improvement.
________________________________________
3. Key Features
â€¢	YAML-based Pipelines â€“ Infrastructure as Code (IaC) for defining pipelines.
â€¢	Multi-stage Pipelines â€“ Supports different environments like Dev, QA, Staging, and Prod.
â€¢	Service Connections â€“ Secure integration with external tools like AWS, Docker, Kubernetes.
â€¢	Agent Pools â€“ Manages self-hosted or Microsoft-hosted build agents.
________________________________________
4. Security & Access Control
â€¢	Azure DevOps Policies (branch policies, approval gates).
â€¢	Role-Based Access Control (RBAC) to manage permissions.
â€¢	Secure Secrets Management using Azure Key Vault.
========================================

Azure DevOps Organization
An Azure DevOps Organization is the top-level container in Azure DevOps that holds projects, users, and services. It provides centralized management for DevOps processes.
________________________________________
1. Structure of an Azure DevOps Organization
An organization consists of:
â€¢	Projects â€“ Containers for code, pipelines, and artifacts.
â€¢	Teams â€“ Groups within projects for collaboration.
â€¢	Repositories â€“ Source code storage (Git/TFVC).
â€¢	Pipelines â€“ CI/CD workflows for automation.
â€¢	Users & Permissions â€“ Role-based access control (RBAC).

Azure DevOps Projects
A Project in Azure DevOps is a container that holds source code, pipelines, work items, and other DevOps resources. It helps teams collaborate efficiently while keeping resources organized.
________________________________________
1. Features of an Azure DevOps Project
Each project contains the following key components:
a. Repositories (Azure Repos)
â€¢	Stores source code using Git (distributed) or TFVC (centralized).
â€¢	Supports branching, pull requests, and code reviews.
b. Pipelines (Azure Pipelines)
â€¢	Automates CI/CD workflows for building, testing, and deploying applications.
â€¢	Can be configured using YAML or Classic Editor.
c. Boards (Azure Boards)
â€¢	Helps in agile project management using work items, sprints, and Kanban boards.
â€¢	Tracks bugs, tasks, and user stories.
d. Test Plans (Azure Test Plans)
â€¢	Supports manual, exploratory, and automated testing.
â€¢	Helps teams track and improve software quality.
e. Artifacts (Azure Artifacts)
â€¢	Stores package dependencies (NuGet, npm, Maven, etc.) for projects.
â€¢	Ensures secure and scalable package management.
________________________________________

Azure DevOps Server vs. Azure DevOps Services
Azure DevOps is available in two deployment options:
1.	Azure DevOps Services (Cloud-based, SaaS)
2.	Azure DevOps Server (On-premises, self-hosted)
________________________________________
1. Azure DevOps Services (Cloud-based SaaS)
Azure DevOps Services is a fully managed cloud-based DevOps solution hosted by Microsoft.
________________________________________
2. Azure DevOps Server (On-Premises, Self-Hosted)
Azure DevOps Server is an on-premises version of Azure DevOps for organizations needing full control over infrastructure and security.

Git vs. TFVC in Azure DevOps
Azure DevOps supports two types of version control systems:
1.	Git â€“ A distributed version control system (DVCS).
2.	TFVC (Team Foundation Version Control) â€“ A centralized version control system (CVCS).
________________________________________
1. Git (Distributed Version Control System - DVCS)
Git is the most widely used version control system and is the default in Azure DevOps.
Key Features:
âœ” Distributed Version Control â€“ Every developer has a full copy of the repository.
âœ” Branching & Merging â€“ Lightweight branches for parallel development.
âœ” Pull Requests & Code Reviews â€“ Enables team collaboration.
âœ” Offline Work â€“ Changes can be made without an internet connection.
âœ” Integrates with CI/CD â€“ Works seamlessly with Azure Pipelines.
Best For:
âœ… Agile teams using modern DevOps practices.
âœ… Projects requiring frequent branching and merging.
âœ… Teams working remotely or offline.
________________________________________
2. TFVC (Team Foundation Version Control - Centralized)
TFVC is a centralized version control system used in legacy projects.
Key Features:
âœ” Central Repository â€“ All code is stored in a central server.
âœ” Check-in/Check-out Model â€“ Prevents multiple people from editing the same file.
âœ” History Stored on Server â€“ Easier access to project history.
âœ” Permissions on File Level â€“ More granular access control.
Best For:
âœ… Large enterprises with strict version control policies.
âœ… Projects requiring file-based security and permissions.
âœ… Teams that prefer centralized control over code changes.
________________________________________
3. Key Differences:
Feature	Git         (DVCS)	              TFVC (CVCS)
Repository	        Local & Remote	      Centralized
Branching	          Fast & lightweight	  Heavy & expensive
Merging	            Frequent & easy	      Less frequent, complex
Work Offline?      	Yes	                  No
Code History      	Local & Server	      Server only
Check-in/Check-out	No	                  Yes (exclusive locking)
Best For	          Agile & DevOps	      Enterprise & legacy projects
________________________________________



